Text Mining and Natural Language Processing - MS4H05¶

Huge amounts of information can be stored within text data. Whether this is in books, websites, social media posts or product reviews in this instance, text can be a very valuable source of data. However, text data can be difficult to analyse computationally due to how varied and unstructured it can be.

Text mining and natural language processing are fields that work to extract meaningful information from text data. This can be achieved through a variety of methods that clean and transform the text into a structured and useable format that can be interpreted and analysed by a computer.

This report looks at a dataset containing reviews of clothing items written by customers. First the text will be preprocessed, then sentiment analysis and topic modelling will be performed. Finally, a text classification model will be built.

Pre-processing and Text Mining¶

Pre-processing and text mining are essential steps in an NLP project. Pre-processing relates to the process of cleaning and transforming raw data so that it can be used for further analysis. In particular, raw text data can have so much variation and complexity, that it can be very difficult to use without preprocessing techniques being applied. Computers are great at handling numerical data, but text data can be much more complicated. After preprocessing, text mining is the process of extracting usual information and insights from the text data. This section will preprocess the data using various techniques and then draw some initial insights.

The first step is to load the data as a pandas dataframe and view the head of the data to get a quick view of what the dataset looks like. This shows that there are two text columns: "Title" and "Review Text". These text columns contain the title and body of the reviews that will be analsyed. Then there are also additional columns relating to customer feedback scores, and the category of item that was being reviewed. We can also see from the first two rows that there are missing values in the Title column, and there may be in other columns too.

In order to preprocess the text data, a variety of tools will be used. First, the English language model of spaCy has been loaded. spaCy is a useful library for NLP that provides functions for many essential methods such as tokenisation and lemmatisation. The English language model is a pre-trained model that provides the information for this functions to work.

The code block below defines a function that performs all of the required preprocessing for a column of text data.

First, the function performs tokenisation and lemmatisation on the text. Tokenisation breaks down the text into a sequence of smaller units called tokens, which will usually be each individual word. Lemmatisation then reduces these tokens into their base form, or lemma. For example, walk, walking, and walks, would all lemmatise to the root form of walk. This helps standardise different forms of worms for further analysis.

Then, the function uses regular expressions to remove non-alphabetic characters other than the symbols "@" "!" and "?". Regular expressions are sequences of characters that can be used for pattern matching in text data. Here, regular expressions are used to substitute out unnecessary text. Removing punctuation can cause issues in instances such as acronyms, clitics, and contractions. However, for this data set acronyms are unlikely to cause much of a problem. Exclamation marks and question marks have been kept in the data as they can potentially contain information that can be used later on for sentiment analysis. For example, "good!!!" is likely to be more intensely positive than simply "good".

Next, regular expressions are also used to remove websites and email addresses. This is achieved by using the "@" symbol that was kept in the previous step, as well as looking for sub strings containing "com" that would be found in web addresses. Other forms of these could exist, but this should do a good job of removing the majority of this unwanted information.

After that, stop words are removed from the text data. Stop words are common words such as "the" or "a" that appear often but do not provide much information or carry much meaning to the sentence overall. The Natural Language Toolkit (NLTK) has a built-in collection of stop words that have been used here. Both the text data and the stop words are converted into lowercase, and then all stop words are removed from the data. Converting the text data to lowercase helps normalise the data, reducing noise. For example, "Good" and "good" likely carry the same meaning, so making the text all lowercase simplifies the vocabulary.

Each of those steps carry certain risks. Making the text lowercase can remove information regarding intensity, such as "GOOD" Vs "good". Removing punctuation can remove information regarding important contractions such as "don't". All of these steps can and should be changed and edited depending on the specific task to get the best performance. However, this list of steps has been chosen as a good starting point to show how the data can be cleaned and pre-processed.

To finish, the text is joined back up into one complete string with spaces between each word.

In [ ]:
def clean_text(text):
    # Tokenize the text using spaCy and extract lemmas of non-punctuation tokens that are not '!' or '?'
    words = [token.lemma_ for token in nlp(text) if not (token.is_punct and token.text not in ['!', '?'])]
    # Remove non-alphabetic characters except for '@', '!', and '?'
    words = [re.sub(r"[^A-Za-z@!?]", "", word) for word in words]
    # Remove websites
    words = [re.sub(r"\S+com", "", word) for word in words]
    # Remove email addresses
    words = [re.sub(r"\S+@\S+", "", word) for word in words]
    # Remove empty spaces 
    words = [word for word in words if word!='']
    # Get the list of English stopwords
    stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words("english")
    # Convert stopwords to lowercase
    stopwords_lower = [s.lower() for s in stopwords]
    # Convert the list of words into lowercase and then remove stopwords
    words = [word.lower() for word in words if word.lower() not in stopwords_lower] 

    # Join the cleaned words into a single string with spaces in between
    cleaned_text = ' '.join(words)
    
    # Return the cleaned text
    return cleaned_text

To see how that function changes the text, it has been performed on the same example as before. We can see how it is now all lower case and punctuation has been removed except for the "!" characters. Stop words such as "this" have been removed, leaving behind a streamlined review that still captures all of the important information.

Sentiment Analysis¶

Sentiment analysis refers to the extraction of information from text regarding sentiment. Sentiment could mean text classified as positive, negative, or neutral. It could also mean specific emotions such as happy or sad. This is a useful way of getting information on the thoughts and feelings hidden within text data. In this instance, sentiment analysis can allow to gain an understanding of how the reviewer felt and why they might have felt that way. This way negative sentiment can be addressed, and positive sentiment can be reinforced.

To begin with, labelling the data manually gives a frame of reference that can later be used to assess model performance in classification problems. To do this, each review will be given a label of positive, negative, or neutral. In order to see which label each review should get, the ratings data will be used as well as the recommended IND which shows whether or not the customer recommends the product. Plotting this shows that almost everybody who rated the product a 4/5 or a 5/5 did recommend the product, whilst almost everybody who rated a 1/5 or a 2/5 did not recommend the product. Meanwhile, people who rated the product a 3/5 were fairly split on whether or not they would recommend the product.

Based on the above graph, the decision was made to label all reviews with ratings of 4/5 or 5/5 as positive. Meanwhile all reviews with ratings of 1/5 or 2/5 will be labelled as negative, and all reviews with ratings of 3/5 will be labelled as neutral. The below code defines and applies a function that adds this label to a new column in the dataframe. This label is stored as an ordinal variable, with negative being 0, neutral being 1, and positive being 2.

In [ ]:
# A function that computes the rating label based on the rating score
def Rating_Value(value):
    if value >= 0 and value <= 2:
        return 0
    elif value == 3:
        return 1
    elif value >= 4 and value <= 5:
        return 2
    else:
        return None

# Apply the function to create column2
Review_Data['Rating_Value'] = Review_Data['Rating'].apply(Rating_Value)

The first method of sentiment analysis being conducted is using the Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner (VADER). VADER is a rule based method of sentiment analysis that has a pre-built lexicon that analyses the sentiment of a text by assigning a polarity score that will be either positive, neutral, or negative. The below uses VADER on the body of the reviews.

In [ ]:
# Create the VADER sentiment analyzer
analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Define a function to apply VADER sentiment analysis to each row in the DataFrame
def analyze_sentiment_body(row):
    text = row['clean_body']  # Assuming 'preprocessed_text' is the column name
    scores = analyzer.polarity_scores(text)
    # Extract the compound score, which represents the overall sentiment
    sentiment_score = scores['compound']
    return sentiment_score

# Apply the sentiment analysis function to each row in the DataFrame
Review_Data['sentiment_score'] = Review_Data.apply(analyze_sentiment_body, axis=1)

The plot below shows the compound score of the sentiment scores calculated by using VADER. The results show that the overall sentiment is very positive. Almost all of the reviews lie between a sentiment score of 0.75 and 1, with only a negligible amount having negative scores at all. To some extent this is expected, as the dataset is heavily imbalanced and there are far more positive reviews than negative. However, the effect of this is still slightly more than would be expected, which means there may be a positive bias. This could be for many reasons. Maybe the sentiment lexicon used is not well optimised for review data like this. It is also possible that the data cleaning improperly handling contractions has caused issues. This is something that can be assessed later, but the overall conclusion should still be robust even if the effect size may be exaggerated.

The next method of sentiment analysis used was the NRC Word-Emotion Lexicon (NRCLex). NRCLex is a lexicon designed for sentiment analysis that measures things on an emotional level. Each word will have associations with the emotions "anger", "anticipation", "disgust", "fear", "joy", "sadness", "surprise", and "trust". This allows for emotion detection in text which can be further analysed.

The code below defines a function that performs sentiment analysis on the body of the reviews using NRCLex.

In [ ]:
# Perform sentiment analysis using NCRLex
def analyse_sentiment(row):
    text = row['clean_body']
    sentiment = NRCLex(text)
    sentiment_scores = sentiment.affect_frequencies # Calculate affect frequencies
    sentiment_score = sentiment.raw_emotion_scores # Calculate emotion scores
    
    return sentiment_scores, sentiment_score

The function is then applied to the review bodies and two new columns are formed. The two scores represent the affect frequencies and raw emotion scores of the sentiment analysis. The affect frequencies show the relative frequency of each emotion, whilst the raw emotion score represents the strength or intensity of the emotions. Both of these scores will be plotted.

In [ ]:
# Apply sentiment analysis to the preprocessed text column
# Create empty lists to store sentiment scores
sentiment_scores = []
sentiment_score = []
# Iterate over each row with the function
for _, row in Review_Data.iterrows():
    scores, score = analyse_sentiment(row)
     # Append the 'scores' to the lists
    sentiment_scores.append(scores)
    sentiment_score.append(score)

# Assign the scores as new columns in the dataframe
Review_Data['NCRLex_scores'] = sentiment_scores
Review_Data['NCRLex_score'] = sentiment_score

The code below shows the same example review for a jumpsuit that has been used before. This shows the sentiment scores of this review. The NCRLex_score shows the raw emotional scores, with joy being the highest at 5. The NCRLex_scores shows the affect frequency, the relative frequency of all the emotions, showing how many of the emotions such as fear and anger are not present in the review at all. This provides an example of how the NCRLex sentiment analysis works before the results are plotted.

The final method of sentiment analysis used was a Multinomial Naive Bayes model (MNB) for text classification. MNB is a machine learning algorithm based on Bayes's theorem that can be used for many classification tasks.

In order to perform MNB, the text data must be vectorised as most machine learning algorithms require numerical inputs. To achieve this, Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) has been used. TF-IDF multiplies the frequency of a term within a document by the inverse of the frequency of documents containing that term. This transforms the text data into a vector that can be used in MNB classification.

In this instance, the review body text will be split into a training and test set for the machine learning model. The review body will be used as opposed to the title as the bodies should be longer and contain more information. The model will predict if reviews in the test set are positive, neutral, or negative, and accuracy will be calculated using the rating values column previously created. A range of performance metrics are then calculated, and a confusion matrix has been plotted.

Immediately from the results, a problem can be seen. The model predicts almost every single review as being positive. This is likely due to the data being so imbalanced. The vast majority of the reviews are positive, so a model predicting the positive class every time would have deceptively high accuracy. This basic model clearly does not perform well and will need to be looked into further.

Topic Modelling¶

Topic modelling involves the extraction of topic information from text data. It analyses the distribution of words across all the different reviews in the dataset to see if underlying themes and topics can be identified. This can provide insights into what the key topics are that are within the reviews.

The first method of topic modelling used is Hierarchical Dirichlet Process (HDP) which is a model that can be used to identify the ideal number of topics within the corpus. HDP uses a hierarchical structure with broad topics at the top, branching down into smaller subtopics. HDP does not have a fixed number of topics, and flexibly infers the ideal number of topics by looking at the distribution of topic probabilities. The code below performs HDP on the review bodies.

The results show that the HDP model suggests 20 topics are the ideal amount. This will now be used to create an LDA model for further topic modelling.

from gensim.corpora import Dictionary

    texts.append(tokens)

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) is the model that HDP is based on. LDA models the generation of documents under the assumption that every document is built from a variety of topics and that every topic is composed of a variety of words. The code below performs LDA with 20 topics as that was considered the ideal amount by the HDP model.

The results show the 20 topics and assigns each document with its most probable topic. These results will now be plotted for further analysis.

In [ ]:
texts = []  # List to store preprocessed texts

for review in Review_Data['clean_body']:
    tokens = word_tokenize(review)  # Tokenize
    texts.append(tokens)

# Create dictionary and document-term matrix
dictionary = corpora.Dictionary(texts)  # Create a dictionary of unique tokens
corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(text) for text in texts]  # Convert the text to bag-of-words (BoW) format

# Perform LDA
num_topics = 20  # Number of topics to extract
lda_model = models.LdaModel(corpus, num_topics=num_topics, id2word=dictionary, passes=10)

# Print the topics and their top words
#topics = lda_model.print_topics(num_words=10)
#for topic in topics:
    #print(topic)

# Assign the most probable topic to each document
topic_assignments = [max(lda_model[doc], key=lambda x: x[1])[0] for doc in corpus]

# Add the topic assignment to the DataFrame
Review_Data['topic_assignment'] = topic_assignments

To visualise the results of the LDA topic modelling, the pyLDAvis library has been used. This creates an interactive visualisation with a scatterplot showing the relationships between topics, with a closer distance meaning the topics are more similar to each other. The size of the circles shows how prevalent each topic is, and hovering over each circle you can see the percentage of tokens that are in that topic. You can also then view a bar chart of the most relevant terms for each topic and see how they compare to the frequency in the corpus as a whole. This provides a great level of insight into each topic, which topics are the most prevalent, and what terms each topic is composed of. For example, you can clearly see small topics, 10, 16, and 14 are far away from the other topics, indicating they are in their own separate, more similar cluster. Looking at the bar charts, topic 10 contains all of the use of the word "blouse" and topic 14 contains all of the use of the word "sweater. This means those topics can probably be labelled as terms related to blouses and sweaters, and that those topics are more similar to each other than they are to other topics.

The most prevalent topic is topic 9 with contains ~12% of tokens. The words contained in this topic include "size", "small", "large", "fit", "medium", "big", "little" and many other terms to do with size and fitting. Therefore this topic has likely accurately captured size related themes in the text. This also contains a high relevance to the word "order", meaning this topic is likely related to clothes ordered online and how they fit. The most closely related topic to this is topic 18, with the most common words in this topic being "petite", "short", "length", and "long". It is clear these topics are similar due to being closely related to size and fitting. The difference seems to be that topic 18 is more focussed on small sizings, containing all of the frequency of the word "petite" and most of the frequency of the word "short". These two topics provide a good example of how the LDA topic modelling has worked, and it seems to have performed reasonably well, accurately identifying themes in the text regarding the size and fitting of products. A lot of useful information can be drawn from this. For example, topic 15 seems to refer to skirts, topic 3 contains most of the information regarding colour, and topic 1 seems to contain information regarding the customer journey and experience with words such as "store", "try", "see", "buy", "online" and "retailer".

The next method that I implemented was t-SNE to visualise the topics in a 2-dimensional space. t-distributed stochastic neighbour embedding, is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique that can be used to visualize high-dimensional data in two or three dimensions. It can be useful for visualizing clusters, patterns, and trends, and in this case can be used to visualise how the different topics relate to each other, and how well each topic clusters.

The code below implements t-sne for the 20 topics of the LDA model. The plot shows how these topics cluster and group with each other. The topics actually cluster fairly well, with colours operating within different spaces. There is some overlap, and some of the topics appear to cluster better than others, but overall they group well.

This can also provide insights into which topics are more similar to one another, and which themes may be the most related. Overall, visualising the topics in this way can help us understand the underlying structures running throughout the corpus.

import numpy as np
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Fit LDA model and obtain topic distribution for each document
lda_model2 = lda_model  # Replace with your LDA model
topic_distributions = [lda_model2.get_document_topics(doc) for doc in corpus]  # Replace with your corpus

# Find the maximum number of topics across all documents
max_topics = max(len(topics) for topics in topic_distributions)

# Pad shorter topic distributions with zeros
topic_probs = []
for topics in topic_distributions:
    probs = [prob for _, prob in topics]
    probs.extend([0] * (max_topics - len(probs)))
    topic_probs.append(probs)

# Convert topic_probs to a NumPy array
topic_probs = np.array(topic_probs)

# Perform t-SNE on the topic distribution vectors
tsne = TSNE(n_components=2, random_state=42, perplexity=100, learning_rate=30)
topic_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(topic_probs)

#Get the topic indices for each data point
topic_indices = np.argmax(topic_probs, axis=1)

# Plot the t-SNE results with different colors for each topic
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(topic_tsne[:, 0], topic_tsne[:, 1], c=topic_indices, cmap='tab20')
plt.xlabel('t-SNE Dimension 1')
plt.ylabel('t-SNE Dimension 2')
plt.title('t-SNE Plot of LDA Results')
plt.colorbar(label='Topic')
plt.show()

To finish visualising the topic modelling, a network mapping has been used. A network mapping represents the relationship between topics and the most important words in them. The nodes represent each topic or word, and the edges represents the relationships between them. The code below creates a network mapping with a threshold set so that only the most important connections are shown.

The network mapping shows that certain topics such as 5 have no strong connections to other relevant topics, whilst other topics such as topic 4 are very closely linked to a variety of other topics and words.

This provides further information about how the topics relate to each other and the overall topic distribution in the corpus.

It is worth noting that the topic numbers in this networking mapping will be 1 less than in the pyLDAvis display as here the index starts at 0 rather than 1. Comparing the two visualisations can provide a great deal of insight into the underlying themes in the data. For example, 4 and 8 in the network mapping (5 and 9 in the pyLDAvis display) are shown to be connected by the word "size". This connection is not immediately clear in the pyLDAvis display as the topics overall aren't that similar, but when you hover over either topic, it then confirms they do both contain a high frequency of the word "size". This shows how a combination of methods is best when performing topic modelling.

import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have an LDA model named 'lda_model' with 'num_topics' topics

num_topics = 20

# Set the threshold for edge weights
threshold = 0.03


# Create a network graph
G = nx.Graph()

# Add nodes for each topic
for topic_id in range(num_topics):
    G.add_node(topic_id)
    G.add_node(topic_id, label=f'Topic {topic_id}')

# Iterate through the topics and their word distributions
for topic_id, topic_words in lda_model.show_topics(num_topics=num_topics, formatted=False):
    for word, prob in topic_words:
        if prob >= threshold:
            G.add_node(word, label=word)
            G.add_edge(topic_id, word, weight=prob)


# Create a layout for the graph using force-directed layout
pos = nx.spring_layout(G, seed = 25)

# Draw the network graph
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
nx.draw_networkx(G, pos=pos, node_color='lightblue', node_size=500)
plt.title('Topic Network Graph')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Further Exploration: Text Classification¶

Text classification can be used for sentiment analysis, to determine the seniment or emotions of a new piece of text. This can be achieved through a variety of models, often in which the model is trained on labelled data as a supervised learning model.

One of the most state of the art models for NLP is Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT). BERT is a transformer based model developed by google, that is pre-trained on a very large corpus of text data, and is able to understand a lot more of languages nuances than most models. BERT can be a very powerful tool for text classification and sentiment analysis, however it is very computationally expensive and can take a very long time to run. In the code below, I have implemented BERT on the dataset. However, as it is so computationally expensive, I have not yet been able to run it. It seems like the code works, but from what I've researched it could take many hours, if not days to fully run. Therefore I have commented the code out for now, so you can skip past it. I have instead used an XGBoost model for text classification to see if that performs better than the multinomial naive bayes model did. Maybe by the time of the presentation I'll have been able to run this code too!

""" 
import torch
from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader
from transformers import BertTokenizer, BertForSequenceClassification, AdamW

tokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')

# Define the dataset class
class SentimentDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, data, tokenizer, max_length):
        self.data = data
        self.tokenizer = tokenizer
        self.max_length = max_length

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        text = self.data['clean_body'].iloc[index]  
        label = self.data['Rating_Value'].iloc[index] 

        encoding = self.tokenizer.encode_plus(
            text,
            add_special_tokens=True,
            max_length=self.max_length,
            padding='max_length',
            truncation=True,
            return_tensors='pt'
        )

        return {
            'input_ids': encoding['input_ids'].flatten(),
            'attention_mask': encoding['attention_mask'].flatten(),
            'label': torch.tensor(label, dtype=torch.long)
        }

# Create train and test datasets
train_data = Review_Data.sample(frac=0.8, random_state=42)
test_data = Review_Data.drop(train_data.index)

train_dataset = SentimentDataset(train_data, tokenizer, max_length=128)  
test_dataset = SentimentDataset(test_data, tokenizer, max_length=128)  

# Create data loaders
batch_size = 16  # Modify batch size if needed

train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)
test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=batch_size)

# Initialize the BERT model
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', num_labels=3)  
device = torch.device('cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')
model.to(device)

# Define the optimizer and loss function
optimizer = AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=2e-5)
loss_fn = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

# Train the model
model.train()
total_loss = 0

for epoch in range(3):  
    for batch in train_loader:
        input_ids = batch['input_ids'].to(device)
        attention_mask = batch['attention_mask'].to(device)
        labels = batch['label'].to(device)

        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(input_ids, attention_mask=attention_mask, labels=labels)
        loss = outputs.loss
        total_loss += loss.item()
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

    print(f'Epoch {epoch + 1}: Average Loss: {total_loss / len(train_loader)}')
    total_loss = 0

# Evaluate the model
model.eval()
correct = 0

with torch.no_grad():
    for batch in test_loader:

        attention_mask = batch['attention_mask'].to(device)
        labels = batch['label'].to(device)

        outputs = model(input_ids, attention_mask=attention_mask)
        predictions = torch.argmax(outputs.logits, dim=1)
        correct += (predictions == labels).sum().item()
        total += labels.size(0)

accuracy = correct / total
print(f'Test Accuracy: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%') """

Conclusion¶

Overall, text mining and natural language processing methods have been shown to be incredibly useful at gathering insights from text data. Preprocessing can enable text data to be more interpretable by computers for analysis. Sentiment analysis can provide insights into how customers think and feel about particular products and the retailer overall. Topic modelling helps draw a detailed picture of the underlying structure and themes of the corpus as a whole.

For this dataset, these methods have revealed a lot of interesting information. For example, sentiment analysis has shown that the size and fit of many different products may be a common problem. Sentiment analysis has also shown that positive emotions such as joy and anticipation are most commonly felt, and most of the reviews are very positive. Dissapointment in the quality and materials of certain products is also something that could be a common problem. Topic modelling has shown that there are many underlying themes in the reviews such as product size, colour, and customer journey. This can be used to better understand the common things customers are thinking about to identify what should be focused on in the future.

There are a huge number of different ways that this sort of analysis could be expanded. All different item categories could be looked at and analysed with more time. Which words are triggering particular emotions, such as joy or anger, the most often could also be looked into to gain a deeper level of insight into customers emotional responses. Text classification models could be further tuned, and more cutting edge methods could also be looked into.

Text data contains a huge wealth of information, and further analysis could draw out even more depth of knowledge.
